## Problem 1 ##

*Chapter 7, Exercise 2 (p. 298)*

When `λ = ∞`, the penalty term dominates the objective function that we are minimizing, and the (least square) solution for `g` comes from minimizing the sum of squares with the constraint `g′′(x) = 0` for all `x`. Here, `m` makes a difference.

However, when `λ = 0`, then the minimizing function interpolates the data; $y_i = f(x_i). Note that in this case the function does not have to be linear.

## Problem 3 ##

*Chapter 7, Exercise 5 (p. 299)*

### Part A ###

$\widehat{g} _2$ would likely have the smaller training RSS since it's a higher-order polynomial.

### Part B ###

$\widehat{g} _1$ would likely have the smaller test RSS. The higher-order polynomial function $\widehat{g} _2$ has an extra degree of freedom, causing it to possibly overfit the training data, resulting in worse test results.

### Part C ###

The two functions are equivalent when `λ = 0`.

## Problem 5 ##

*Chapter 7, Exercise 9 (p. 299). In part (d), the book instructs you to fit a regression or cubic spline with 4 degrees of freedom. Use 7 degrees of freedom instead (3 knots)*

<div id="part-a" class="section level3">
<h3>Part A</h3>
<pre class="r"><code>set.seed(8)
library(MASS)
library(boot)
library(splines)
df = Boston

# Cubic polynomial regression to predict nox using dis.
fit = lm(nox ~ poly(dis, 3), data = df)
summary(fit)</code></pre>
<pre><code>##

<pre class="r"><code>dis.range = range(df$dis)

plot(nox ~ dis, data = df)
lines(dis.seq, prediction, lwd = 4, col = 'blue')</code></pre>

</div>
<div id="part-b" class="section level3">
<h3>Part B</h3>
<pre class="r"><code>N = 10
reps = rep(NA, N)
for (i in 1:N) {
  fit = lm(df$nox ~ poly(dis, i), data = df)
  reps[i] = sum(fit$residuals^2)
}
reps</code></pre>
<pre><code>##  [1] 2.768563 2.035262 1.934107 1.932981 1.915290 1.878257 1.849484
##  [8] 1.835630 1.833331 1.832171</code></pre>
</div>
<div id="part-c" class="section level3">
<h3>Part C</h3>
<pre class="r"><code>NUM_FOLDS = 20
reps = rep(NA, N)
for (i in 1:N) {
    fit = glm(df$nox ~ poly(df$dis, i), data = df)
    reps[i] = cv.glm(df, fit, K = NUM_FOLDS)$delta[2]
}
plot(1:N, reps, xlab = 'Polynomial degree', ylab = '20-fold CV error', lwd = 2, col = 'blue', type = 'l')</code></pre>
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," title alt width="672" /></p>
<p>We pick <code>1</code> as the best polynomial degree, since it has the lowest cross-validation error.</p>

## Problem 6 ##

*Chapter 7, Exercise 11 (p. 300)*

<div id="part-a" class="section level3">
<h3>Part A</h3>
<pre class="r"><code>set.seed(51)  # Because 51 is edgy.

N  = 100
x1 = rnorm(N)
x2 = rnorm(N)
e  = rnorm(100, sd = 1)

y  = 1.2 + 2.3*x1 + 3.4*x2</code></pre>
</div>
<div id="parts-c-b" class="section level3">
<h3>Parts C &amp; B</h3>
<pre class="r"><code>b1 = 5
a  = y - b1*x1
b2 = lm(a ~ x2)$coef[2]</code></pre>
</div>
<div id="part-d" class="section level3">
<h3>Part D</h3>
<pre class="r"><code>a  = y - b2*x2
b1 = lm(a ~ x1)$coef[2]</code></pre>
</div>
<div id="part-e" class="section level3">
<h3>Part E</h3>
<pre class="r"><code>NUM_ITERATIONS = 1000
b0 = rep(NA, NUM_ITERATIONS)

for (i in 1:NUM_ITERATIONS) {
    a     = y - b1[i] * x1
    b2[i] = lm(a ~ x2)$coef[2]
    a     = y - b2[i] * x2
    fit   = lm(a ~ x1)
    if (i &lt; NUM_ITERATIONS) {
        b1[i + 1] = fit$coef[2]
    }
    b0[i] = fit$coef[1]
}
plot (1:NUM_ITERATIONS, b0, type = 'l', xlab = 'Iteration #i', ylab = 'Beta values', ylim = c(-5, 5), col = 'grey')
lines(1:NUM_ITERATIONS, b1, col = 'blue')
lines(1:NUM_ITERATIONS, b2, col = 'green')
legend('bottom', c('b0', 'b1', 'b2'), lty = 1, col = c('grey', 'blue', 'green'))</code></pre>
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," title alt width="672" /></p>
</div>
<div id="part-f" class="section level3">
<h3>Part F</h3>
<p>Compare your answer in (e) to the results of simply performing multiple linear regression to predict Y using X1 and X2. Use the abline() function to overlay those multiple linear regression coefficient estimates on the plot obtained in (e).</p>
<pre class="r"><code>NUM_ITERATIONS = 1000

lm.fit = lm(y ~ x1 + x2)
plot (1:NUM_ITERATIONS, b0, lwd = 5, type = 'l', xlab = 'Iteration #i', ylab = 'Beta values', ylim = c(-5, 5), col = 'grey')
lines(1:NUM_ITERATIONS, b1, lwd = 5, col = 'cyan')
lines(1:NUM_ITERATIONS, b2, lwd = 5, col = 'green')
abline(h = lm.fit$coef[1], lty = 'dotted', lwd = 2, col = rgb(0, 0, 0, alpha = 0.5))
abline(h = lm.fit$coef[2], lty = 'dotted', lwd = 2, col = rgb(0, 0, 0, alpha = 0.5))
abline(h = lm.fit$coef[3], lty = 'dotted', lwd = 2, col = rgb(0, 0, 0, alpha = 0.5))
legend('bottom', c('b0', 'b1', 'b2', 'Multiple regression'), lty = c(1, 1, 1, 2), col = c('grey', 'cyan', 'green', 'dark grey'))</code></pre>
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," title alt width="672" /></p>
<p>The coefficients from multiple regression match the coefficients from backfitting perfectly.</p>
</div>
<div id="part-g" class="section level3">
<h3>Part G</h3>
<p>Only really needed to do one iteration.</p>
</div>
